When you have a family or born underprivileged due to the location where you're born or the family you were born to, it is difficult to come away from that with prosperity. Many of the Chartwells workers, since I have taken the time to actually get to know them personally since I've been a student here for the past three years, are living in lackluster conditions. When you are born underprivileged, you are warranted less opportunities than the majority of the student populations is inherently used to. Basically, what I am saying is that the students here have no idea how privileged they are (me as well) to be born to a family or to have some sort of special circumstance to help boost them to educational prominence. Most, if not all, of the Chartwells workers (which I worked with a portion of them at the BUC the past year and a half) grew up in areas where there were inadequate schools and insufficient resources granted to them. I am not excusing their attitudes. I am one to say that no matter what circumstance, your attitude and behavior should not be dependent on your emotions, which is an essential piece to Christianity and the life I strive to live. However, you can only imagine the struggles they have to go through to help get their families by on a week to week, day to day basis. So please, whenever your next thought on bashing these workers for their poor attitudes, understand the same opportunities that may have been granted to you and I, was not in their blessing growing up. They are people worth loving and treating awesomely just as you and I are.
